      In all of our representations, we see evidence that if the input of our function, <m>(x,y)</m>, approaches <m>(0,0)</m>, then the output of our function goes to 3, regardless of the direction or way we approach <m>(0,0)</m>. We generalize this idea with the following definition.
    </p>
  </example>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given a function <m>f = f(x,y)</m>, we say that <m>f</m> <term>has limit <m>L</m> as <m>(x,y)</m> approaches <m>(a,b)</m></term> provided that we can make <m>f(x,y)</m> as close to <m>L</m> as we like by taking <m>(x,y)</m> sufficiently close (but not equal) to <m>(a,b)</m>. We write
        <me>
          \lim_{(x,y)\to(a,b)} f(x,y) = L
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    Our work in <xref ref="LimitEx1" /> showed that the limit of <m>f(x,y)=3-x-2y</m> as <m>(x,y)</m> approaches <m>(0,0)</m> is 3. Symbolically, this looks like
    <me>lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow(0,0)} 3-x-2y = 3</me>
  </p>
  <p>
    To investigate the limit of a single variable function, <m>\lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m>, we often consider the behavior of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from the right and from the left. Similarly, we may investigate limits of two-variable functions, <m>\lim_{(x,y)\to(a,b)} f(x,y)</m> by considering the behavior of <m>f</m> as <m>(x,y)</m> approaches <m>(a,b)</m> along a particular path. Remember that the multivariable function situation is more complicated because there are infinitely many ways in which <m>(x,y)</m> may approach <m>(a,b)</m>, so we will not be able to check every possible path. In the next activity, we see how it is important to consider a variety of those paths in investigating whether or not a limit exists.
  </p>
